[crisp-react](https://github.com/winwiz1/crisp-react) has the server and client projects.

Similarities with your setup:&lt;br/&gt;
 - Projects are located in `server/` and `client/` directories&lt;br/&gt;
 - Each project has its own `package.json` and `node_modules/`&lt;br/&gt;
 - Uses Typescript&lt;br/&gt;
 - The client side static files are reachable for the server&lt;br/&gt;
 - Auto build. There are usage scenarious when the client is automatically rebuilt when source code changes. That is called Live Reloading. The same applies to the server code, it gets rebuilt automatically as you type the source code changes. 

What&#39;s different:&lt;br/&gt;
 - No `css/` directory as CSS for each client component is in the component&#39;s .tsx file&lt;br/&gt;
 - No `html/` directory because .html files are auto-generated. 

Having one single `package.json` and `tsconfig.json` doesn&#39;t sound like a great idea because dependencies and settings are rather different.

If your kernel module is including the header from `/usr/include/linux`, something is indeed going wrong there: the files in `/usr/include/linux` are for use by userland applications (see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/9094237), not kernel modules. 

Instead, your module should be including the header file in the kernel source.

For what it&#39;s worth, that seems to be the default on my system. If I compile this not-a-kernel-module:

```
#include &lt;linux/netfilter.h&gt;

void my_fn(void) {
	struct nf_hook_ops ops;
}
```

with a Makefile identical to your snippet, it succeeds, and when I run `make V=1`, make reports that it is calling `gcc` with flags to skip the standard include directories, and add the `include` directory at the correct location:

```
gcc ... -nostdinc ... -I./include ...
```

If yours does not, something is going wrong there, but it&#39;s hard to tell what without looking at the code.

